<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-011-281 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 479 626</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Nov 13 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>General Software announces royalty-free DOS for demos. (DEMO DOSoperating system for demo disks) (Product Announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mallory, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Software Inc. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   DEMO DOS (Operating system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionOperating systemsSoftware packagesMS-DOSCompatible SoftwarePromotion of Product.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>General Software Announces Royalty-Free DOS For Demos 11/13/91 REDMOND,WASHINGTON, U.S.A., 1991 NOV 13 (NB) --  General Software has announced theavailability of DEMO DOS, a royalty- free MS-DOS compatible operating systemfor demo disks.andM;The new program is designed for developers of DOS-based software todistribute demo disks of their products using a royalty-free, legitimate copyof DOS, making their demonstration self-bootable.andM;General Software claims that its product is compatible with MS-DOS 3.31 bysupporting the same API (applications program interface) and device drivers.andO;It also supports Command.Com.andP;  DEMO DOS can be duplicated with the DISKCOPYcommand, or by copying the files and running a program called INSTBOOT, whichcomes with the kit.andM;A DEMO DOS distribution kit sells for $495, and gives the purchaser unlimitedrights to duplicate and distribute the operating system for promotional usefor a period of one year.andM;General Software Chairman and CEO Steve Jones told Newsbytes that the companywas not concerned with legal problems with Microsoft.andP;  Jones said somecustomer had asked the same question.andP;  According to Jones: &quot;We have oursanitization letter, where we tell them (the customer) how we did it on ourown.&quot;andP;  Jones was formerly employed by Microsoft as the Technical Lead forLanMan 386, and later worked with the Windows NT group, writing LAN (localarea network) software.andM;Asked by Newsbytes what the motivation is for developers to use the $495 kitinstead of simply transferring the DOS system files to their demo disks,Jones said one of the advantages is that his product will boot without makingany changes to the user's PC environment.andM;Jones told Newsbytes that he has offered to sell General Software toMicrosoft, but said Steve Ballmer, senior vice-president at Microsoft,declined.andM;Jones said General Software also distributes Booter Tool Kit for $99, whichmakes a disk bootable, but does not offer any other DOS services.andM;(Jim Mallory/19911113/Press contact: Steve Jones, General Software,206-391-4285, FAX 206-746-4655)</TEXT></DOC>